## Using the GOV.UK Wallet Sandbox mock Status List Service

You can use the real [Status List Service](/issue-credentials/status-list/) to [check the status of a real credential](/issue-credentials/status-list/statuslist/#check-a-credential-39-s-status). When you are testing your verification service, you must use the mock Status List Service to check the status of your test digital driving licence.

### Check the status of a test digital driving licence

You can check the status of a test digital driving licence you have issued using [the same process as the Status List Service](/issue-credentials/status-list/statuslist/#check-a-credential-39-s-status). However, you must use the following URLs:

- https://status-list-mock.wallet-onboarding.integration.account.gov.uk/.well-known/jwks.json
- https://status-list-mock.wallet-onboarding.integration.account.gov.uk/t/`{STATUS_LIST_IDENTIFIER}` 

The value of `STATUS_LIST_IDENTIFIER` will be unique to your test credential.

The URLs for the mock Status List Service are different to those in production. You must not use live credential status information for your testing environment.

### Understand the capabilities of the mock Status List Service

The mock Status List Service has limited functionality compared to the Status List Service. You should understand these differences and consider them in your testing.

The mock Status List Service will:

- cover only a small number of token indices, resulting in a much shorter encoded string than the Status List Service
- support two statuses per token: 0x00 (valid) and 0x01 (invalid)
- set the value of the `exp` timestamp to the expiry of the credential plus 30 days, in seconds
- set the `ttl` claim to 2592000, which is 30 days in seconds

There is more information available about the [`exp` and `ttl` claims](/issue-credentials/status-list/statuslist/#token-status-list-request-example-request-response-payload).